Yeah I feel this! So much tension between the known/unknown and rigid/emergent in an SOW...

Ha not really. My best advice for SOWs:

1) build up trust with your POC in smaller engagements (e.g. Workshop) so that the SOW can be loose

2) scope around time not deliverables (value pricing is fine, but harder when designing for emergence)

3) treat POC as an ally (it's you + POC against finance)
Also Lindsay Slaby is a total SOW nerd and writes some good stuff on LI about contracts etc: https://www.linkedin.com/in/lindseyslaby

Yeah I am indeed an outlier with #2. I find that you can get away with very loose SOWs with time based engagements (e.g. "Tom will be in the office two days a week") and that you can end up with very long engagements that way too...

Wrote a bit about that here: https://tomcritchlow.com/2021/01/26/kairos/

It might depend on your definition of negative / positive infinity....

If you assume:

+ infinity is bigger than any positive number
- infinity is less than any negative number

Then:

I think it's fairly straightforward through proof by contradiction. I.e. assume there exists a positive number bigger than infinity (false by definition)

or assume there exists a negative number less than -ve infinity (false by definition)
